he, Basse-Normandie, France":"Coutances, Manche, Lower Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"SAY","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Sai in Orne or Say in Indre, France, perhaps so called from a Gaulish personal name <i>Saius</i> + the Latin locative suffix <i>-acum</i> (see also French name 3 below).","English: nickname, perhaps for someone who made or sold say, a type of woollen cloth, or for an habitual wearer of clothes made of this material, from Middle English <i>sai(e)</i> ‘say’ (Old French <i>saie</i>, from Latin <i>saga</i>, plural of <i>sagum</i> ‘military cloak’). See also   Sayer  .","French (southern): topographic name from <i>saix</i> (from Latin <i>saxum</i>) ‘rock’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example, Say in Loire, Saix in Tarn and Vienne, Le Saix in Hautes-Alpes, or Les Saix in Isère."],"variants":[{"name":"Sey","meanings":["English and Scottish: probably a variant of   Say   particularly prevalent in Scotland.","Dutch and Flemish: from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigiheri</i> (see   Seger  ).","West African (Ghana): Akan (Fante) name of unexplained etymology."]},{"name":"Sayer","meanings":["English: common occupational name from Middle English <i>sayer</i>, a phonetic variant of   Sawyer  , which in Wales and neighboring English counties may have been reinforced by the synonymous Welsh <i>saer</i> ‘carpenter’ and everywhere by a possible borrowing into Middle English of Old French <i>seieor</i>, <i>saieur</i> ‘sawyer’.","English: rare occupational name perhaps denoting an assayer of metals, or a servant who tasted his lord's food before serving, from Middle English <i>saiour</i> ‘assayer, tester’ (a shortened form of Old French <i>assaiour</i>, ultimately from Late Latin <i>exagium</i>, a derivative of <i>exagmināre</i> ‘to weigh’).","English: rare occupational name for a professional reciter or minstrel, from Middle English <i>seier(e)</i> ‘speaker’."]},{"name":"Saye","meanings":["English: variant of   Say  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Saje</b>: nickname for someone with very dark, sooty hair, derived from the root of <i>sajast</i> ‘sooty’, or directly from <i>saja</i> ‘soot’.","West African (Liberia): from the personal name <i>Saye</i>, found among the Mano (Mah) people, denoting a first-born boy."]}]},{"name":"RUELLAN","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Catalan (<b>Rullán</b>): from the personal name <i>Rullán</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Roland  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Roland","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"RUELLAN DE SAY was born in 1130, in France. He had at least 1 daughter with PETRONILLE DE GRENTENTEMESNIL. He died in 1210, in Italy, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1130–1210":"1130–1210","1135–1212":"1135–1212","1152–1205":"1152–1205","1205":"1205","10 September 1205":"10. september 1205","1212":"1212","1135":"1135","1210":"1210","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","Durazzo ligurie Italie":"Itaalia","France":"Prantsusmaa","Gaël, Rennes, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France":"Gaël, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, Prantsusmaa","Coutances, Coutances, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Coutances, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1130–1210":"1130–1210","1135–1212":"1135–1212","1152–1205":"1152–1205","1205":"1205","10 September 1205":"10. syyskuuta 1205","1212":"1212","1135":"1135","1210":"1210","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","Durazzo ligurie Italie":"Italia","France":"Ranska","Gaël, Rennes, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France":"Gaël, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, Ranska","Coutances, Coutances, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Coutances, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1130–1210":"1130–1210","1135–1212":"1135–1212","1152–1205":"1152–1205","1205":"1205","10 September 1205":"10 septembre 1205","1212":"1212","1135":"1135","1210":"1210","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","Durazzo ligurie Italie":"Italie","France":"France","Gaël, Rennes, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France":"Gaël, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, France","Coutances, Coutances, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Coutances, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France","lifeSummary":"RUELLAN DE SAY est né en 1130, à France. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec PETRONILLE DE GRENTENTEMESNIL. Il est décédé en 1210, à Italie, à l’âge de 80 ans."},"de":{"1130–1210":"1130–1210","1135–1212":"1135–1212","1152–1205":"1152–1205","1205":"1205","10 September 1205":"10. September 1205","1212":"1212","1135":"1135","1210":"1210","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","Du